  "local_port": 53566,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much money in charitable donations can a person deduct from his/her taxes before being taxed on his/her donations in the US?",
  "response": "In the United States, the tax deduction for charitable donations depends on several factors, including the taxpayer's adjusted gross income (AGI), the type of charity, and whether the taxpayer itemizes deductions on their tax return.\n\nFor tax years 2023 and 2024, the general rule is that cash contributions to qualified public charities can be deducted up to 60% of the taxpayer's AGI. For contributions to certain private foundations, veterans organizations, or fraternal societies, the limit is 30% of AGI. For appreciated assets (like stocks) donated to public charities, the limit is 30% of AGI, and for private foundations, it's 20% of AGI.\n\nIf the total charitable contributions exceed these limits, the excess can be carried forward for up to five subsequent tax years.\n\nIt's important to note that to claim these deductions, a taxpayer must itemize their deductions on Schedule A of Form 1040, rather than taking the standard deduction. The standard deduction for 2023 is $13,850 for single filers and $27,700 for married couples filing jointly. In 2024, these amounts are projected to rise to $14,600 and $29,200, respectively.\n\nThere is also a special provision allowing taxpayers who do not itemize to deduct up to $300 ($600 for married couples filing jointly) in cash contributions to qualified charities for tax years 2023 and 2024.\n\nAs tax laws can change and individual circumstances vary, it's always advisable to consult with a tax professional for personalized advice.",
